    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-17T17:31:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-17T17:31:00-05:00" n="1186"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1186">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">641.74/6–1753: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1186<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Kingdom</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-17T18:31:00-04:00"
                            >June 17, 1953—6:31 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8010. For the Ambassador. In connection with the President’s reply<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d1186fn1">Transmitted in telegram 8011, <ref target="#d1187">
                            <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> to <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName>’s June 15
                    message and instructions on Egypt being cabled to you<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d1186fn2">See telegram 8013 to London, <ref target="#d1188">Document
                            1188</ref>.</note> Department is airpouching (1) <persName
                        corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName>’s message (2) General <persName
                        corresp="#p_RGS1">Robertson</persName>’s memo which was appended<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d1186fn3">Not printed.</note> (3) Under Secretary’s memo of March
                        10<note n="3" target="d1186fn3">Not printed.</note> setting out his
                    understanding of US–UK agreement on negotiating flexibility between Cases A and
                        B.<note n="4" xml:id="d1186fn4">See <ref target="#d1061">Document
                        1061</ref>.</note> This agreement is referred to in today’s instructions. If
                    Items (1) and (2) above not available through Foreign Office and required
                    urgently, they will be cabled on request.</p>
                <pb facs="0396" n="2098" xml:id="pg_2098"/>
                <p>Re Item (3): During March talks <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName>
                    received a very strong telegram from <persName corresp="#p_CWS1"
                        >Churchill</persName> objecting to any compromise with Case A. This
                    discussed at length between Under Secretary and <persName corresp="#p_ESA1"
                        >Eden</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName>
                    finally assented. Following is substantive portion of Item (3): <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“We had rather long talk during which I pointed out that British
                            apprehension with regard to second alternative (B) was largely matter of
                            interpretation of most desirable result; i.e. base in continuous
                            operation immediately available on D-Day, and less desirable but
                            acceptable alternative of base which could be put in effective operation
                            within 60 days. I left quite certain British would agree to this since I
                            was sure views expressed in Prime Minister’s cable were his alone and
                            not as he indicated those of <persName corresp="#p_SFM1">Slim</persName>
                            and <persName>Alexander</persName>. Monday morning, a few minutes before
                            our meeting with the President, the Prime Minister agreed to this
                            arrangement which was accepted by the President as a negotiable basis.
                            The President indicated that our military representatives should arrange
                            to ensure ‘proper technical supervision and inspection’ of
                            communications and other heavy installations at the base.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF2">
                            <hi rend="strong">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                            </hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
